ic actor, dualisms, and individualism. Also of interest in chapters and follow up discussions are the relations between essentialism and emergentism in complex systems theory.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aKnowledge, Theory ofvCongresses. 0aPhilosophy, Moderny19th centuryvCongresses. 0aRationalismvCongresses. 4aPhilosophy : Philosophy. 4aPhilosophy : Social Philosophy. 4aSociology : Social Thought. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / General.2bisacsh1 aLee, Richard E., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aPetitot, Jean, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSayer, Andrew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aThompson, Evan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWallerstein, Immanuel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013z978311148737340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438434421423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438434421/original  a978-3-11-148737-3  SUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles